column2:
ITACA Protocol at Urban Scale is a multi-criteria assessment system for the evaluation of environmental sustainability of an urban context. Starting from a set of basic assessment items, the ITACA Protocol Urban Scale aims to provide a final performance score, indicative of the sustainability level of the urban settlement. The constituent elements of the evaluation method can be summarized as follows:
- a set of evaluation items, called criteria;
- a set of quantities, called indicators, which allow to quantify the performance of the urban area in relation to each criteria. The criteria are  distributed in a series of thematic areas that try to define the complexity of urban quality; governance; urban morphology; landscape integration; quality of the design (bld./site); public spaces; urban metabolism; biodiversity; adaptation; mobility / accessibility; social and functional diversity; economic-social effects.

column12:
The ITACA Urban Scale Protocol is structured according to three hierarchical levels: Areas, Categories and Criteria. (e.g. Area: Economy, Category: Access to residence, Criterion: Economic accessibility to residential rent)
The Areas represent macro-themes that are considered significant for the purpose of assessing the environmental sustainability of an urban context. In the ITACA Protocol at Scala Urbana there are 11 areas:
▪ Governance;
▪ Town planning aspects;
▪ Quality of the urban landscape;
▪ Architectural aspects;
▪ Public Spaces;
▪ Urban metabolism;
▪ Biodiversity;
▪ Adaptation;
▪ Mobility/Accessibility;
▪ Society and Culture;
▪ Economy.
The Categories deal with particular aspects of the areas. The Criteria represent the evaluation items of the protocol and each criterion is associated with one or more physical quantities that make it possible to quantify the
performance of the urban area in relation to the criterion considered through the attribution of a numerical value. These quantities are represented by indicators. Each area includes several categories (in variable number depending on the area considered), each of which deals with a particular aspect of the topic to which it belongs. The categories are, in turn, divided into criteria, each of which explores a particular aspect of the belonging category. Finally, the Criteria represent the evaluation items of the method and are used to characterize the performance of the building at the beginning of the evaluation process.
